The characters were hardly believable and women in the storyI'm not entirely sure what I expected from this "novel" but I did not care for it at all. The characters were hardly believable and women in the story were extremely one-dimensional. This read like someone trying to write philosophy like a novel and it just fell flat. I did not enjoy this at all. I know some people love this novel, and that's fine, it was just not at all interesting to me. This book is a great combination of nature writing, ecolSlaght and his team take you through some rugged, beautiful wilderness in far eastern Russia. title: The Premonition: A Pandemic Story
author: Lewis, Michael
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Michael Lewis has a talent that I love. He's able to dig down into situations and historical events and find the people that are many layers below whaMichael Lewis has a talent that I love. He's able to dig down into situations and historical events and find the people that are many layers below what we see day in and day out. And he seeks these people out because they are the ones who see something with more clarity than anyone else. He's done that yet again with "The Premonition." I loved reading how each of these people were able to see the threat of a pandemic, and what to actually do about, years ahead of time. The only problem was that they were many layers down, so their ideas didn't always rise to the top. I couldn't put this book down even though I knew where it was headed. I highly recommend it if you're interested in science, the flow of information in power structures, and the determination of human beings who really care about their profession and their craft....more

review: I don't believe Bigfoot exists, but I find the underlying belief systems fascinating. Pyle does a nice job of mixing beautiful nature writing (he ventI don't believe Bigfoot exists, but I find the underlying belief systems fascinating. Pyle does a nice job of mixing beautiful nature writing (he ventures into the areas where Bigfoot sightings occur) with the history of how we got to this level of belief. Pyle explores native legends, human stories of the "wild man," tales that get twisted over time, and sketchy evidence that gets blown out of proportion. He also shares stories that have yet to be debunked. It's a fascinating, funny, and sometimes spooky book. I'm not convinced Bigfoot exists, but there are definitely some intriguing questions that still remain unanswered about the forests of the Pacific Northwest. ...more

review: Cantu provides perspectives that I had not read about before in terms of the U.S.-Mexico border. I found the book to be a humanizing look at what happCantu provides perspectives that I had not read about before in terms of the U.S.-Mexico border. I found the book to be a humanizing look at what happens in the deserts and mountains of the southern United States. The book was poetic at times and I was really pulled in by the last section where he attempted to help Jose as much as he could. We need more stories like this to help others hear the stories of what happens in the borderlands. After reading this, I came to Goodreads to give it a rating and to write a short . I was shocked to see some of the 1-star s, with some people saying that this was a "cop-loving" story about how hunting down humans was some kind of game or adventure. I never found this to be true at all while reading this. I don't see where this perspective comes from, as Cantu was simply telling his story about what it is like down on the border. Never did I get the sense that he was a "human hunter" or that he relished what he did. He seemed like people I know: a complicated human being seeking perspectives to understand the world around him....more

review: It was always going to be hard for Andy Weir to follow-up "The Martian" because it was such a great book. The science in "Artemis" is interesting, funIt was always going to be hard for Andy Weir to follow-up "The Martian" because it was such a great book. The science in "Artemis" is interesting, fun, and original, since Weir had to basically invent a lunar city. That's where I would give the book more stars than just three. But when it comes to plot and characters, it falls flat. The characters are predictable, one-dimensional people and Weir's ability to write a female protagonist runs into some unfortunate obstacles (jokes that simply don't work, inner monologue that is questionable at best). The story itself can be riveting at times, but that mainly happens because of the setting (1/6 Earth's gravity, moon dust that will tear you up, habitats where fire & chemicals could kill you in an instant). Overall, it was a fun, quick read, but I really hope that Weir works on his characters and story for his 3rd novel. If he can improve that, and keep his science clear, the 3rd novel could be better than "The Martian."...more

review: This book is beautiful. Jahren does such a wonderful job of weaving her scientific pursuits with the story of her life in labs and the field. Books liThis book is beautiful. Jahren does such a wonderful job of weaving her scientific pursuits with the story of her life in labs and the field. Books like this are hard to put down because they are written in such a unique style, at times almost wandering into a kind of poetic/scientific language. Plus the relationship she has with her lab partner Bill makes you smile, scratch your head, laugh, cry, and hope all at the same time. I highly recommend this book for a variety of reasons: to peer behind the scenes at scientific research, to investigate the deeper parts of our lives, and to make us think about those we are closest to, especially our friends and colleagues, and how much they mean to us in our lives. ...more

review: This had some fun science fiction elements and a neat premise, but it could have been much better. The problem was with character development and usagThis had some fun science fiction elements and a neat premise, but it could have been much better. The problem was with character development and usage, foreshadowing issues, and lack of depth in terms of certain situations.For example, when characters are introduced they are fully-fleshed-out and they seem incredibly important, and then some of them just fade into the background, almost useless to the plot. Also, one high profile character dies midway through the story. The narrator makes it seem as if there will be all kinds of problems from here on out due to their loss. Yet the story goes on without a hitch. There are multiple times when the dangers of space travel are brought up. Things like "We'll be so close to the sun! Danger! Asteroid belt! Danger!" and then nothing at all happens with those areas of space. Time was spent explaining what could happen and how they were protecting their ship from it, and then NOTHING HAPPENS.The ending was kind of neat, but it all felt quite rushed and required tons of explanation on behalf of the characters and narrator. That could have been unveiled better throughout the last third of the book. Also, the parts of the story that included cameras and filming seemed like they were thrown in there with no purpose or point. They were useless scenes. The editor should have just dumped all of those.But I still enjoyed the overall story!...more

my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This is one of the finest pieces of non-fiction I've read in years. Not only is the investigative journalism spot-on, but the author crafts the story This is one of the finest pieces of non-fiction I've read in years. Not only is the investigative journalism spot-on, but the author crafts the story in such a way that it reads like a great narrative with mystery, surprise, and fear. This book opened my eyes to the opiate epidemic in the United States. I knew that it was a problem, but I had no idea of how it started, who it impacted, nor the players involved. I cannot recommend this book enough, especially because Quinones shows us that opiate addiction through OxyContin, black tar heroin, and other pills is not relegated to the back alleys and shadowy places of our society. Opiate addiction is affecting all races and classes. Teenagers are dying from overdoses. Workers are going into doctors with a shoulder injury, getting a prescription, and ending up dead a few years later. They become addicted and keep trying to find that perfect high. If you're looking for a new read, pick this up. You will learn so much from it. ...more

Yes, a new style exists heThe imagination of the author is quite stunning, but I didn't care for the book because the author went a little overboard. Yes, a new style exists here, with many excellent characters, ideas, and alternative ways of thinking about this genre, but it was as if the author just said to himself, "Hey, I'm just going to keep inventing new stuff on every page." It reminded me of "Lord of the Rings" how every single object has four names and different histories. That's a neat device, but if you run with it too much, you lose the plot and the character development. So bravo to how imaginative this was. The cup just runneth over a bit too much....more

review: A friend of mine introduced me to Ingersoll about a year ago. I started reading bits and pieces of his work and was fascinating by his depth of intellA friend of mine introduced me to Ingersoll about a year ago. I started reading bits and pieces of his work and was fascinating by his depth of intellect and his remarkable speaking ability. This book helped me to see quite a bit more of who he was. His courage was something to behold. His thoughts on religion, secularism, free thought, and the law were well ahead of their time and he faced quite a bit of scrutiny and invective from his colleagues. However, his incredible eloquence and intelligence helped him to fill halls to capacity and, often times, had audiences spilling into the street just to get a chance to hear him or meet him.This is a brief biography but it's a good starter for those interested in one of the great thinkers of 19th century America....more

author: Finkel, David
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This is, without a doubt, one of the finest books I've read in years. David Finkel takes you inside the lives of a handful of soldiers who have returnThis is, without a doubt, one of the finest books I've read in years. David Finkel takes you inside the lives of a handful of soldiers who have returned from the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan. This was the kind of book where I went into it thinking I knew exactly how it would be written, how the soldiers' lives would be described, etc. I picked it up because it was on so many must-read lists. It did not disappoint at all and it turned the tables on all of my predictions.These soldiers, and their families, have had their lives thrown into the shredder, and Finkel spares nothing in his descriptions of their day-to-day activities. You get wrapped up in the little bureaucratic battles they deal with and you are floored by the depths of their depression and pain. This is not a happy book for the most part. There are small victories here and there. This book takes you deep into the emotional centers of these men and women and you feel like you are feeling their pain, feeling it flow through you like a cold liquid.Books like these should probably be required reading for citizens living in a democratic republic like ours. Finkel shines a light on the problems of our soldiers that are hiding in the corners of their minds. They may try to repress their pain and their anger, but it is there and it must be dealt with....more

author: Wendel, Tim*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I enjoyed this book because I'm a big baseball fan and a Cardinal fan. Wendel's coverage of baseball in this book is very enjoyable. And that's what hI enjoyed this book because I'm a big baseball fan and a Cardinal fan. Wendel's coverage of baseball in this book is very enjoyable. And that's what he should have focused on.The baseball portions of the book are really the heart of the story. I had two complaints about this book. First, Wendel didn't need to talk about football, basketball, the Olympics, or the events of 1968 much at all because it took away from the baseball story. It was as if he was trying to cover as much as he could but couldn't decide how much of each sport/event to put in the book. There's nothing wrong with covering the other sports and events of '68 but he gives them short shrift so you don't end up knowing much about those things at all. They are just tiny side stories in comparison to the baseball.The other problem I had was the way it was organized and Wendel's writing style. He would jump from one thing to another quite often. One section, for example, included talking about the Cardinals, then the next paragraph was about Bob Gibson seeing MLK Jr. at an airport, the next paragraph was about what they would have talked about if they had talked, and then the final paragraph was about MLK's enjoyment of sports. The book had odd paragraph structures like that from time to time. They just didn't work.Overall, though, if you just want a history of the '68 baseball season, I recommend it....more

review: This is a fantastic book. There are two main stories here: the general history of the U.S. nuclear weapons program, from the Manhattan Project to the This is a fantastic book. There are two main stories here: the general history of the U.S. nuclear weapons program, from the Manhattan Project to the end of the Cold War, mixed together with the riveting narrative of the Damascus Incident. The Damascus Incident involved a Titan II ICBM in Arkansas in the early '80s. I won't tell you what happened because you need the suspense of the story to keep it going.Schlosser does an excellent job of writing these two stories. His research is top-notch and precise. These stories will scare you like you simply would not believe. The U.S. has come so close, so many times, to a nuclear accident that it's not even funny. This is a must-read for anyone concerned with the future of nuclear weapons or understanding the human desire to defend itself as a society. ...more

author: Pessl, Marisha*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This book starts out with some spooky stuff going on. The writing at the beginning will make you look over your shoulder and immediately pulls you in.This book starts out with some spooky stuff going on. The writing at the beginning will make you look over your shoulder and immediately pulls you in. Then the story dies down a bit and you get into the nitty gritty of the plot. However, by the time the climax starts to build, you're in for the long haul and even more spookiness. Plus, it's got an ending that will keep you guessing.I had picked this book up based on very positive s and I enjoyed it too. Pessl does a great job of bringing you down with her into the deep, dark underworld of Stanislas Cordova, a movie director who scares the living daylights out of anyone that watches his films. Sometimes the descriptions of his world are a bit over the top, but you get used to it.I only had a couple of problems with this book and they were rather large ones. Pessl's writing style has a tic in it. She tends to vastly overuse simile and metaphor, so almost any description of someone, something, or some event has to be described in an unnecessary way. Sometimes those descriptions can be a nice addition to the story, but more times than not it gets in the way of the story. The second problem are the three main characters (McGrath, Hopper, and Nora). They don't seem to have very deep or detailed personalities. They're mainly just represented as people who are caught up in something they don't understand. They just have reactive emotional states similar to anyone else you know. Nothing grand or specific.Other than those two things, I still really enjoyed the book....more

review: I read "Year of the Flood", which is the 2nd book in this trilogy, before I read "Oryx and Crake." They actually work either way, but after reading thI read "Year of the Flood", which is the 2nd book in this trilogy, before I read "Oryx and Crake." They actually work either way, but after reading this fantastic book, I want to go back and read the 2nd book again.Oryx and Crake is imaginative, but in a way that is also quite unsettling. It takes place in our future, one possible future, in which we are doing really horrible things to ourselves and the Earth. In other words, it's where we're headed if we don't make any changes to what we currently do. People's behaviors are still pretty terrible and this society only brings out the extremes. I know Atwood doesn't like to consider it science fiction, instead calling it "speculative fiction." Either way, she does a great job of capturing some of our worst tendencies in this story.Atwood has a unique ability to exhibit the deeper emotions, feelings, and thinking of characters than other authors I have read. There are times when you feel so sorry for Jimmy, the main character, and other times when you hate him. Crake is creepy but his storyline arc is long, so we may see him in a different light when this is all over. This book helps me ask myself the question, "Where are we going as a species and as a society?" The story also takes the old phrase "everything that rises must converge" to a new level of thought....more

title: Death from the Skies!: These Are the Ways the World Will End...
author: Plait, Philip*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: My most recent read was from astronomer Phil Plait, who writes the Bad Astronomy blog over at Slate. "Death from the Skies" chronicles all of the possMy most recent read was from astronomer Phil Plait, who writes the Bad Astronomy blog over at Slate. "Death from the Skies" chronicles all of the possible ways that our planet, and life as we know it, could be destroyed by non-terrestrial natural events. This is definitely not light reading nor does it always perk you up, but it is funny, highly informative, and humbling. Plait's description of our solar system, galaxy, and universe help you to appreciate our position in the cosmos. But how do we survive? Here's how.Plait covers a wide range of deadly outer space culprits in an attempt to show you just how powerful nature is. The list includes: gamma ray bursts from black holes, solar flares/coronal mass ejections, asteroid impact, comet impact, galactic collision (that's a slow death), and many others. Each chapter starts with a fun little 2-3 page story of humans observing these things from Earth, and they can be a bit scary. After that, the writing is filled with excellent science writing mixed with Plait's clever humor. You come away from this book with far more knowledge of nature than just what can kill us. Plait does an excellent job of explaining how so many different natural forces work, from gravity to chemistry to geology to quantum mechanics.Here's the good news: most of these things are not going to kill us. The chances of gamma ray bursts or galactic collisions happening are slim. However, the two chapters that I enjoyed the most are actually the chapters the tell the story of our two most likely killers: solar radiation and asteroid/comet impacts.Plait makes a great case near the end to increase funding towards protecting our planet against solar radiation and impacts from extra-terrestrial bodies like comets and asteroids. There are some great ideas, scientists, and programs out there that just need more funding to get their plans off the ground. A coronal mass ejection could wipe out our power grid and send us plunging into medieval times. It could even damage our ozone layer, which leads to huge long-term problems. And we all know what an asteroid or comet impact could do. The dinosaurs know all about that. But we can prevent these, the most likely problems, if we just work harder at it.This was a fun, engaging read that I recommend to folks who enjoy a good science book, especially those of you who enjoy astronomy....more

review: This book was flat-out fantastic. It's one of the most engaging and thrilling novels I've read in awhile. It's based on a real event, the Franklin ExpThis book was flat-out fantastic. It's one of the most engaging and thrilling novels I've read in awhile. It's based on a real event, the Franklin Expedition to the find the Northwest Passage to Asia through the arctic. We don't know much about what happened to the expedition, but Dan Simmons is brilliant by filling in the details for you. And scaring you quite a bit in the process.There are a few characters, too, that you become especially attached to because they reveal themselves in stages throughout the story. The characters become darker as the story grows due to the fact that conditions worsen in the expedition. The descriptions of the arctic and the cold and the disease and the pain are so real that you sometimes feel like putting on more clothing or getting out one more blanket. You feel for these men, not just because they were real at one point in time, but because Simmons writes them so well. It's as if you're watching them do all of this right outside your window.This story mixes man v. nature, science fiction, mythology, European v. Native attitudes, the slow descent into the inner core of who man really is, and countless other intriguing storylines. You find yourself turning the pages quicker and quicker. And just when you thought you might have something figured out, Simmons scares you again with something out-of-the-ordinary. I can't tell you too much without giving away the story. If you enjoy a good historical fiction with sci-fi mixed in, pick it up. I highly recommend it....more

review: **spoiler alert** I was disappointed by this book. The first book, The Passage, started off great and then slowed down and became strange, disjointed,**spoiler alert** I was disappointed by this book. The first book, The Passage, started off great and then slowed down and became strange, disjointed, and rather weak near the end. This book did so as well but more quickly.It is difficult to say where this book's focus lies. You meet some characters and spend awhile reading about them and then they're dead. Oh, but wait, they are the ancestors of some people who are living right now. Who cares? What did that have to do with anything?I found most of the characters in this book not believable. It's as if you simply took some people from 2012 and plopped them down into a different setting. There really isn't a sense of 100 years of apocalypse. People still talk the same way, Guilder and his minions still behave the same way, and important details are just left out. How do they find fuel when they're driving the bus towards the east coast? A guiding hand. What? And what was with that scene near the end when Guilder suits up in robes and says, "It's game time"? What was that? That's terrible writing. And then Amy transforms, the Twelve die, and the very next chapter, our heroes are just running the show and behaving like regular folk. No one is grieving, no one seems to be in the depths of depression or anguish because they just destroyed half a city and twelve giant vampire beasts. No, everyone just goes on with their lives. This book lacks energy and fear. It's named "The Twelve" and you barely ever see them. They emerge from beyond the horizon, agree to get put in the back of a semi (?), get transported to a stadium, and then get destroyed by a few humans. How did these demi-gods survive for one hundred years and then just up and get beat in a matter of 10 minutes?Why did Lila change her mind? Why did Lila and the dracs even go to that place that eventually became known as the Massacre of the Field, steal a few people, and then didn't come back for 20 years? What did Cronin feel that it was necessary for a bunch of main characters to be connected by that event? It didn't help anything.I don't think I'm going to read the third book. It's going to be disappointing, just like this one was....more

title: Spillover: Animal Infections and the Next Human Pandemic
author: Quammen, David*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: It feels good to get the reading year started with a science book. David Quammen has written some excellent science and nature essays in the past and It feels good to get the reading year started with a science book. David Quammen has written some excellent science and nature essays in the past and I thought this book, his newest, would be a fun try at his longer work.It did not disappoint.The subject of the book is zoonosis, which is the transfer of a disease from animals to humans. Some of our most famous and deadliest diseases are zoonotic. Quammen travels the globe interviewing doctors, scientists, and patients who have either been infected with or worked with countless bacteria, viruses, or parasites. He chronicles malaria, hendra, hanta, ebola, SARS, flu, HIV, and others. It will definitely open your eyes to how susceptible we are to nature's cruelest bugs. Quammen's writing style can be deep but also contains quick jabs that will spook you like a scene out of a horror film. You'll be reading fascinating pages about different forms of a virus, how it was isolated, the processes used to identify it, etc. and then all of a sudden he tells you a story about someone who got it and how it spread. The hair on the back of your neck stands up as the science gives way to the gruesome reality of these diseases. The only part of the book I did not care for was a section he included in the HIV chapter. In it, he creates a sort of historical fiction of how the virus may have traveled from southeast Cameroon over a century ago into the Congo. It's pretty good fiction writing but I didn't feel like it meshed at all with the rest of the science writing in the book. It was kind of an outlier section that made you feel like the book was going in the wrong direction.I learned a ton from this book. It helped dispel certain urban legends and pieces of misinformation about quite a few viruses. The chapter on SARS will keep you riveted and the chapter on HIV will make you proud of the hard-working scientists who traced HIV back over 100 years into Africa's past.If you're into science and want something that will both pull back the curtain and scare you at the same time, I recommend this heartily....more

title: Wild: From Lost to Found on the Pacific Crest Trail
author: Strayed, Cheryl*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This was somewhere between and 3 and a 4 for me. First, the negatives. I found the book fairly predictable, which isn't always a negative, but I thougThis was somewhere between and 3 and a 4 for me. First, the negatives. I found the book fairly predictable, which isn't always a negative, but I thought that maybe she would prove me wrong and have an "ah ha!" moment within. The writing was good, but not stellar. Sometimes she would describe something very beautiful or deep, but other times I felt like those descriptions or accounts seemed forced.However, the positives of this book outweigh the few negatives. I'm a sucker for an outdoors story. Ms. Strayed does an excellent job of recounting her life along the trail and how it connected to her life off the trail. Some people read books like this and claim that they are obvious, that it's common sense that time in nature will heal you or open you up to new things. And I say to them, "So what if it's obvious?" We need more books like this that help people to see that there are simple, delightful things in life and that we probably don't do them nearly as often as we should.I've always been a proponent of the idea that if something is important, you make the time for it. Often I will hear (and actually say myself) people say, "I don't have time for that." Sure you do. You just have different priorities. Ms. Strayed reminds us that you need to think about your priorities from time to time in order to live a better, happier life.There's a scene near the end when she has finished hiking the trail and she meets a lawyer near an ice cream shop. He is amazed at her journey and how far she has come. She tells him that if she can do it, anyone can do it, including him. He says, "No, I'm too busy." One of the things I try to remind myself is that I don't want to be that lawyer throughout my life. Sure, I will take care of the things that need to be taken care of and I will do my job as best I can, but I never want to say that I'm too busy to do something that I know I'll love and cherish forever. We shouldn't have to look back on our lives one day and realize that we didn't do the things we loved. Do them now. Ms. Strayed reminds us to do them now....more

review: Another great book by Elaine Pagels. Her vast knowledge of biblical literature and ancient languages helps put the Book of Revelation in its proper plAnother great book by Elaine Pagels. Her vast knowledge of biblical literature and ancient languages helps put the Book of Revelation in its proper place in world literature. She gives this mysterious and cryptic story a proper context and identifies the symbols, codes, and language in order to help the reader see what the book truly is: a quasi-political/religious criticism and warning of the Roman Empire at that time in history. Plus, she also helps shine a light on the fact that there were countless other revelation stories but these were either lost or destroyed by early leaders of the church since they disagreed with more 'canonical' works. The writing is a bit dry but if you can get past that, this is a fascinating book that will help you understand one of the stranger parts of the New Testament....more

The book is set in the rural areas of Bois Sauvage, Mississippi in the days leading up to Hurricane Katrina, and Esch’s inner monologue, combined with the narrator’s omniscience and use of beautiful language, really make this book shine. The story follows the Batiste family through their trials and tribulations as they prepare for the coming of the hurricane, although it seems as if their father is the only one who really knows how bad it’s going to be. Esch’s brother Skeetah, who fights dogs as a hobby, has a dog named China that has more personality than some of the other human characters. With the narrator describing the brutal vividness of their lives in Bois Sauvage, combined with Skeetah and China’s unique relationship, this book is hard to put down. title: The Swamp: The Everglades, Florida, and the Politics of Paradise
author: Grunwald, Michael
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I enjoy finding local bookshops when we travel and buying a book or two about the place we're in. Normally I go for a local author or a history of theI enjoy finding local bookshops when we travel and buying a book or two about the place we're in. Normally I go for a local author or a history of the place. On our trip to Sanibel we found a great little gem of a place called simply the Sanibel Bookshop. This place had everything, including this book, "The Swamp." I had to buy it.This book is fascinating, mainly because it mixes the history of South Florida from the early Spanish days up through the modern day with the environmental history of the Everglades. Before reading this book I had little knowledge of what the Everglades are but now that I have finished the book, I want to head straight back down to Florida and see them.The Everglades are one of the most unique ecosystems on the planet. You won't find any other environmental structure like them on Earth. And they're dying. We're killing them with sprawl, chemicals, and bureaucratic neglect. Grunwald does a nice job of weaving the story of how man has lived with the Everglades ever since the Seminole and Miccosukee Indians lived there (and some still do).There are times when the author gets a little distracted with one person's story or some silly government red tape crap, but overall this book inspired me to think more deeply about places like the Everglades. I've been a fan of our national parks for a long time, but now I have a better sense of how some of our parks need more than just a legal protection; they need engaged, knowledgeable bodyguards to keep them from disappearing forever....more

review: This book is less about zombies and the conflict and more about the main character's thoughts on the history of the former society and a possible futuThis book is less about zombies and the conflict and more about the main character's thoughts on the history of the former society and a possible future society. He's frustrated and has no compass to guide his future actions with. Sure, he's been in survival mode for some time, but he cringes whenever people bring up the past as it was. I found myself loving the language that Whitehead uses in this story because it makes you question all of the things that you do, day in and day out. Now that society has collapsed, why would we want to have the same society all over again? Why would we want to live lives that take us away from the truest things out there? Why would we want to recreate the same lifeless jobs and activities that drain us of desire, of passion? I enjoy my life but I can see what he's getting at overall. Here's an opportunity to create something new, to learn from the mistakes, and to embrace something more human, tied to the natural, not the artificial.Of course you have to read it to find out what happens in the end. This book surprised me by how good it was. I highly recommend it. It will make you appreciate the most important things in your life more....more

title: The Swerve: How the World Became Modern
author: Greenblatt, Stephen
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I was not entirely sure what this book was about until I started reading it. It had received such good s that I had to check it out. I'm so gladI was not entirely sure what this book was about until I started reading it. It had received such good s that I had to check it out. I'm so glad I did because this was my favorite book so far this year. In a nutshell, the author shows how a rare book collector in the 1400's finds one of the only remaining copies of Lucretius's "On the Nature of Things" and has it copied from a monastic library. From there, the work sees a resurgence of interest, much to the chagrin of the Catholic church and other traditional institutions at the time. After that the work becomes a huge hit with the great thinkers of the Renaissance and afterward, up to Thomas Jefferson. You have to read it to get all the details, but the thesis is that the rediscovery of Epicureanism, which has been grossly misconstrued by centuries of traditionalists, lies at the root of our modern world. It was Lucretius's work that helped people to see the world in a completely different way and thus made the world "swerve" towards a new future. My only complaint was that Greenblatt only spends one chapter (the last one) connecting great thinkers and "On the Nature of Things". I would have liked to have seen more writing on how famous thinkers adopted it and used it in their ideas and their writing. Overall though this book was fascinating and fun to read!...more

review: When I first heard of this book, I assumed it was a type of self-help book. In a way it is, but it's written by John Tierney of the NYT so it reads moWhen I first heard of this book, I assumed it was a type of self-help book. In a way it is, but it's written by John Tierney of the NYT so it reads more like the traditional solid non-fiction that I enjoy. The book's ideas center on the human concept of willpower, what it is, and how it works. The research is pretty interesting and each chapter shows you examples of studies in which humans are tested on their ability to use willpower. What I didn't know is that willpower is like a fuel tank; you can use up all your willpower before the day is over and it can be hard to get back. When our willpower is low, we make very poor decisions. Willpower actually uses up glucose so when you are hungry, you make very bad decisions, so you need to refuel in order to have energy to actually be decisive. I recommend this to anyone who wants to understand the human brain a little better and figure out how you can use some of their great tips to make better decisions and organize your days a little more....more

review: I know some people are hot and cold on this book, but I found the characters, especially Schwarz and Skrim, to be quite believable. I also liked Owen'I know some people are hot and cold on this book, but I found the characters, especially Schwarz and Skrim, to be quite believable. I also liked Owen's character quite a bit. This book is more than just baseball and I found myself making quite a few peeks into my memory banks from Moby Dick, Emerson, and a few coming of age novels. The reason I enjoyed this book so much is that it is about the art of fielding, but not the type of fielding that you find on a baseball field. The characters are all searching for ideas about who they really are and who they are trying to be. They don't know how to deal with the problems that life has given them. They sometimes don't even know how to build their souls, like Affenlight and Owen talked about at the end of the book. For me, the story rings with the idea that you leave a little bit of yourself in different points of time throughout your life, and those places and people become a part of you as well. Baseball itself doesn't teach these young men how to be grown men. It's their relationships with each other that help them try to become better human beings, but even after some maturity you still fail, like Affenlight did.Like Franzen's Freedom, I enjoyed this book because it seemed real TO ME. In my experience, I have known people like this. They are not caricatures. I know that people have had these kinds of feelings in their lives. Harbach isn't just creating some silly archetypes. He has actually pulled emotions from real life and made good characters out of them. If you don't agree, then I think it's a matter of your own personal experiences. People like this exist. ...more

review: This is between a 3 and a 4. The author does a smashing job with her declassified sources and pulls back the curtain on the real Area 51. Simply put, This is between a 3 and a 4. The author does a smashing job with her declassified sources and pulls back the curtain on the real Area 51. Simply put, it was a CIA/Air Force airfield for many decades. Plus it doubled as an area for nuclear testing research. I was fascinated by the Oxcart and Blackbird projects that she details extensively in the book.The one big fault with the book is the last chapter, focusing on what is known as The Roswell Incident. The legend: aliens crashed a spacecraft at Roswell, NM and the remains were taken to Area 51 for research and study. Jacobsen claims, according to one source (an original engineer from the early days of 51), that the craft was of Soviet origin and the inhabitants/pilots were genetically-altered humans created by former Nazi doctor Josef Mengele, the Angel of Death. Although this counter-story is intriguing and more on the rational side of Occam's Razor, I do not believe it because she only relies on one source to claim it is true. If she had a few more, then we'd be on to something.Overall an interesting read into the history of the U.S. spy program with the Soviets....more

Really all it does is remind the reader that every life requires balance, and that balance can be achieved through disconnection from technology from time to time. The author uses some interesting examples, including the conversation between Socrates & Phaedrus, to highlight other people in history who had the same problems 21st century techno users have.If you use technology a lot and want a little food for thought, pick it up and give it a read. title: The Panic Virus: A True Story of Medicine, Science, and Fear
author: Mnookin, Seth
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: Seth Mnookin wrote a tremendous book and I am so happy to have read it. This book stands up for science and shows, in great detail, how there are no lSeth Mnookin wrote a tremendous book and I am so happy to have read it. This book stands up for science and shows, in great detail, how there are no links between vaccines and autism. The author does a great job of showing the evidence for the benefits of vaccines and how groups claiming vaccines are bad have no evidence at all. The book covers the international epidemiological studies, the Special Masters decision of 2008, the decades of disease prevention, and many, many other examples of science working for the benefit of people. The author also does an excellent job of highlighting the problems, errors, willful ignorance, and lack of scientific expertise and knowledge of many so-called "experts" on the side of the anti-vaccine crowd. The one figure who needs to apologize to families everywhere is Jenny McCarthy, who continues to spout myths and people believe her.I'm glad I read this book. I sympathize greatly with families who have autistic children and I hope that they one day find out why their children have this disorder and that they may find a cure or method of prevention. However, until that day arrives I believe that scientific knowledge has shown that there is no link between one of our great achievements, vaccines, and autism....more
